Myxomatosis, Russia
-------------------
Information received on (and dated) 30 Sep 2009 from Dr Nicolay Vlasov,
CVO, Veterinary services, Ministry of Agriculture and Food, Moscow, Russia

Summary
Report type: Immediate notification
Start date: 26 Aug 2009
Date of first confirmation of the event: 26 Aug 2009
Date submitted to OIE: 30 Sep 2009
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 2007
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: Myxomatosis virus
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (basic), necropsy
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks
Outbreak 1: Nelazskoye, Cherepovetsky, Vologodskaya Oblast
Date of start of the outbreak: 26 Aug 2009
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: village
Species: rabbits
Susceptible: 60
Cases: 10
Deaths: 0
Destroyed: 8
Slaughtered: 2
Affected population: animals kept by a small private owner.

Outbreak 2: Sapoon, Vachsky, Nizhegorodskaya Oblast
Date of start of the outbreak: 07 Sep 2009
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: village
Species: rabbits
Susceptible: 1670
Cases: 64
Deaths: 1
Destroyed: 1
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: animals kept by a small private owner.

Outbreak 3: Korotovo, Cherepovetsky, Vologodskaya Oblast
Date of start of the outbreak: 26 Aug 2009
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: village
Species: rabbits
Susceptible: 83
Cases: 81
Deaths: 2
Destroyed: 78
Slaughtered: 3
Affected population: animals kept by a small private owner.

Outbreak 4: urban settlement Sosnovskoye, Sosnovsky, Nizhegorodskaya Oblast
Date of start of the outbreak: 07 Sep 2009
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: village
Species: rabbits
Susceptible: 1108
Cases: 153
Deaths: 34
Destroyed: 119
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: animals kept by a small private owner.

Outbreak 5: Popad'ino, Pavlovsky, Nizhegorodskaya Oblast
Date of start of the outbreak: 07 Sep 2009
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: village
Species: rabbits
Susceptible: 1362
Cases: 389
Deaths: 92
Destroyed: 92
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: animals kept by a small private owner.

Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 5
Species: rabbits
Susceptible: 4283
Cases: 697
Deaths: 129
Destroyed: 298
Slaughtered: 5

Outbreak statistics
Species: rabbits
Apparent morbidity rate 16.27 per cent
Apparent mortality rate 3.01 per cent
Apparent case fatality rate 18.51 per cent
Proportion susceptible animals lost* 10.09 per cent
* Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction,
and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection -- under investigation

Control measures
Measures applied
- movement control inside the country;
- disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s);
- modified stamping out;
- no vaccination;
- no treatment of affected animals.

Measures to be applied
- vaccination in response to the outbreak(s)

Laboratory name and type: Federal Scientific Institution, All-Russia
Scientific Institute of Veterinary Virology and Microbiology, Pokrov
(National laboratory)
Species: rabbits
Test: reverse transcription - polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR)
Test date: 07 Sep 2009
Result: positive
Rabbits virus isolation: 07 Sep 2009 positive

Laboratory name and type: State Institution Vologda Regional Veterinary
Laboratory (National laboratory)
Tests and results
Species: rabbits
Test: histological test
Test date: 26 Aug 2009
Result: positive

Future Reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

--
communicated by: ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The outbreaks have occurred at locations which are a large distance from
each other in central Russia -- 2 in Vologodskaya Oblast and the other 3 in
Nizhegorodskaya Oblast. Please see the map attached to the OIE report.

Myxomatosis is reported periodically in Europe, according to OIE. Russia
reported 24 outbreaks in 2005 and 2 in 2007. Relatively large outbreaks
over the last five years have been reported in Denmark (2006, 2007),
Estonia (2005), Italy (2005-2008) and Poland (2005-2008).

The following countries in Europe have also reported outbreaks:
Armenia (2005)
Belgium (2005-2009)
Czech Republic (2005-2009)
Germany (2006)
Luxembourg (2008)
Netherlands (2005-2007)
Portugal (2005-2008)
Romania (2005-2006)
Slovenia (2005-2007)
Spain (2005-2007)
Switzerland (2007-2008)
UK (2006-2008)

Details of the outbreaks can be obtained from the OIE WAHID database
<http://www.oie.int/wahis/public.php>.

Myxomatosis has a fascinating history, having been deliberately introduced
in Australia as a biological control in 1950. It also seems to elict
popular culture references. For more information on this and a very brief
clinical description, please see the Mod comments in Myxomatosis, rabbits -
Tunisia (Sousse, Monastir): OIE 20070224.0674. - Mod.PC]
